  <span id="freeText14995217764044572360" style="display:none">This is an unusual book. The story revolves around two boys who grow up in Philadelphia and enlist in the army to fight in WWII. The characters are what make the novel unusual. Birdy is a strange, introverted, scrawny kid who becomes obsessed with birds and with wanting to fly. He eventually enters the world of birds so completely that he believes himself to be one. His friend, Al Columbato, is a tough kid who is into sports, bodybuilding and girls. They seem to be polar opposite personality types, but they have a deep and enduring bond. The vivid narrative switches back and forth between their viewpoints, past and present. <br />	After they go off to war, and Al is severely injured in combat, he is brought in by the army to visit Birdy in a psychiatric hospital. Birdy is locked in a solitary cell, where he squats and hops around like a bird, and only eats when food is fed to him in the manner that a baby bird is fed. The army psychiatrist hopes that Al will be able to lead Birdy out of this delusional existence and back to reality.<br />	Al talks to Birdy about their childhood exploits and eventually about his experiences in combat. We learn that Al viewed himself as essentially weak and cowardly in combat, not a tough guy at all. Al muses about the nature of reality and mental illness, questioning what it means to be sane and displaying disdain and suspicion for the psychiatrist. Interspersed with Al’s story are flashbacks from Birdy’s perspective, which reveal the progression of his intense interest in and identification with pigeons at first, and later, canaries. The fascinating perspectives of both the main characters reveal the author’s deep and detailed understanding of birds, as well as of humans, and also the harsh, gut-wrenching experience of horrific combat. It is a great, off beat read. <br /></span>
