  <span id="freeText8621946587987096371" style="display:none">If this was a little shorter or if I liked birds even a bit, I'd have liked it a lot more. As it is, birds are an alien being to me, and honest to god I have no interest in them. I could appreciate that there is this boy who, in his boyhood, develops an intense interest in them, to the extent that he dream-creates a nest with one of them - but I didn't need so many pages of feeding and breeding the canaries to know this. Some of it was enough. <br /><br />I found it interesting though that Birdy knows, absolutely, that he's only dreaming it all. He knows he's dreaming within his dream, even though he fully inhabits a bird body in the dream. He also does a weird experiment with the birds - he lets them free-fly after a while, and he builds his dream nest in a tree and doesn't move it even when he notices a cat prowling around. The cat predictably does the cat thing, and then Birdy loses interest in the whole deal. It's like he was tired of it and wrote an ending. Birdy was creative in a weird way, monomaniacal sure, but there wasn't much else wrong with him.<br /><br />Al on the other hand, had nothing to distinguish him as a person. He was regular, someone who had a traumatic experience during the war, and who might have made an impact in any other story but that of the Bird boy. But it is Birdy, and Al is just a sounding board - someone who talks him out of his bird funk after Birdy's own traumatic wartime experience. A psychologist would have served well enough. All in all, the book wasn't bad, but it didn't really speak to me.<br /><br />(For some reason I thought this would involve a kamikaze pilot and was extremely disappointed it didn't).</span>
